Text Cleaning¶

Introduction¶

In this page, I will introduce the methods I used to clean text data, as well as the reasons why I chose to use these methods due to the purpose of transparency. The code that I wrote to clean the data can be found here: https://github.com/anly501/anly-501-project-yeyaxin1103/tree/main/codes/02-data-cleaning

Data 1: Twitter Search Responses (Tweets)¶

Language Used for Cleaning: Python¶

Data Source: https://github.com/anly501/anly-501-project-yeyaxin1103/tree/main/data/00-raw-data/twitter_api_data¶

This data was pulled from Twitter using Twitter API for keyword searching. Due to the reason that this project focuses on the fertility rate issue in East Asia, the response Tweets must contain either one or multiple of these following keyword: “China Fertility”, “Korea Fertility”, “Japan Fertility”, “Hong Kong Fertility”, “Mongolia Fertility”, and “Taiwan Fertility”. The data extraction process was repeated twice due to the limitation of tweet amount, and the results of the response tweets will be combined for the text analysis.

Cleaning Process¶

For the tweets returned from searching, I first converted them from JSON to pandas DataFrame and combined two result sets into one.

In [5]:
# Read JSON file to pandas dataframe
import pandas as pd

def json_to_df(json_response):
    text = []
    id = []
    author_id = []
    created_at = []
    for tweet in json_response:
        text.append(json_response[tweet]['text'])
        id.append(json_response[tweet]['id'])
        author_id.append(json_response[tweet]['author_id'])
        created_at.append(json_response[tweet]['created_at'])
    df = pd.DataFrame({'author_id':author_id, 'id':id, 'created_at':created_at, 'text':text, 'clean_text':text})
    return df

Then I removed hashtags and mentions, hyperlinks, punctuations, and any non-alphanumeric characters as well as the words that have less than three characters from the texts of response tweets.

In [8]:
def text_cleaner(text):
    text = text.lower()
    # removing hashtags and mentions
    text = re.sub("@[A-Za-z0-9_]+"," ", text)
    text = re.sub("#[A-Za-z0-9_]+"," ", text)
    # removing links
    text = re.sub(r"http\S+", " ", text)
    text = re.sub(r"www.\S+", " ", text)
    # removing punctuations
    text = re.sub('[()!?]', ' ', text)
    text = re.sub('\[.*?\]',' ', text)
    text = re.sub('[0-9]+', ' ', text)
    # removing non-alphanumeric characters
    text = re.sub("[^a-z0-9]"," ", text)
    return text

# Tokenization
def tokenization(text):
    text = re.split('\W+', text)
    return text

df['tweet_tokenized'] = df['clean_text'].apply(lambda x: tokenization(x.lower()))

# remove stopwords
def remove_stopwords(text):
    # remove stopwords
    stopwords = nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('english')
    text = [word for word in text if word not in stopwords]
    return text

df['tweet_nonstop'] = df['tweet_tokenized'].apply(lambda x: remove_stopwords(x))

Later on, I performed stemming and lemmatization process on the clean tokenized text for better interpretation and less variety of the words.

In [12]:
# Stemming 
ps = nltk.PorterStemmer()

def stemming(text):
    text = [ps.stem(word) for word in text]
    return text

df['tweet_stemmed'] = df['tweet_nonstop'].apply(lambda x: stemming(x))

# Lemmatization
wordnet = nltk.WordNetLemmatizer()

def lemmatizer(text):
    text = [wordnet.lemmatize(word) for word in text]
    return text

df['tweet_lemmatized'] = df['tweet_nonstop'].apply(lambda x: lemmatizer(x))

Labeling the tweets based on sentiment value

In [14]:
sia = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()

def sentiment_label(df, colName):
    sentiment = []
    label = []
    for txt in df[colName]:
        score = (sia.polarity_scores(txt))['compound']
        sentiment.append(score)
        if score >= 0.05:
            label.append("positive")
        elif score < 0.05 and score > -0.05:
            label.append("neutral")
        else:
            label.append("negative")
    df['sentiment'] = sentiment
    df['label'] = label
    return df

df = sentiment_label(df, 'clean_text')
